<h2>Topic 6.8 — Causation in the Imperial Age</h2>
<div class="region-card region-causation">
<h3>🔄 Synthesizing Unit 6</h3>
<div style="overflow-x:auto;">
<table class="compare-table">
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Imperial Form</th>
<th>Example</th>
<th>Tools of Control</th>
<th>Key Consequence</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Settler colony</strong></td><td>Australia, Algeria, Southern Africa</td><td>Mass European settlement, land seizure, indigenous displacement</td><td>Fundamental demographic and cultural transformation</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Administrative colony</strong></td><td>British India, French Indochina, Congo</td><td>Small European elite ruling through local intermediaries; export economy</td><td>Restructured economies for metropole benefit; nationalist reaction</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Informal / economic empire</strong></td><td>Qing China, Ottoman Empire, Latin America</td><td>Unequal treaties, loans, foreign-owned firms, gunboat threats</td><td>Lost economic sovereignty without losing the flag</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Protectorate</strong></td><td>Egypt, Korea (Japan), Tunisia</td><td>Local rulers kept on the throne under imperial supervision</td><td>Facade of independence; tight strategic and economic control</td></tr>
